# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: base-editing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:base-editing/apobec] A mechanism of generating protein diversity is mRNA editing.
[src:base-editing/apobec] The APOBEC family of proteins perform mRNA modifications by deaminating cytidine bases to uracil.
[src:base-editing/apobec] The N-terminal domain of APOBEC-like proteins is the catalytic domain, while the C-terminal domain is a pseudocatalytic domain.
[src:base-editing/apobec] More specifically, the catalytic domain is a zinc dependent cytidine deaminase domain and is essential for cytidine deamination.
[src:base-editing/apobec] The positively charged zinc ion in the catalytic domain attracts to the partial-negative charge of RNA.
[src:base-editing/apobec] In the case of APOBEC-1, the mRNA transcript of intestinal apolipoprotein B is altered.
[src:base-editing/apobec] RNA editing by APOBEC-1 requires homodimerization and this complex interacts with RNA-binding proteins to form the editosome.
[src:base-editing/apobec] The resulting structure interacts with the codon CAA at codon 2153 and deaminates it into UAA, producing a stop codon that results in mRNA that is translated into the intestinal apoB-48 isoform.
[src:base-editing/apobec] For other APOBEC-modified transcripts such as in the site-specific deamination of a CGA to a UGA stop codon in neurofibromatosis type 1 (*NF1*) mRNA, the resulting proteins are predicted to be truncated as well, although these transcripts are possibly degraded.
[src:base-editing/apobec] C-to-U modifications do not always result in the truncation of proteins.
[src:base-editing/apobec] For example, in humans/mammals they help protect from viral infections.
[src:base-editing/apobec] APOBEC family proteins are widely expressed in cells of the human innate immune system.
[src:base-editing/apobec] These enzymes, when misregulated, are a major source of mutation in numerous cancer types.
[src:base-editing/apobec] When the expression of APOBEC family proteins is triggered, accidental mutations in somatic cells can lead to the development of oncogenes, cells which have the potential to develop into a tumor.
[src:base-editing/apobec] APOBEC proteins are further expressed in attempt to regulate tumor formation.
[src:base-editing/apobec] This makes APOBEC proteins a helpful marker for diagnosing malignant tumors.
[src:base-editing/apobec] A 2013 review discussed the structural and biophysical aspects of APOBEC3 family enzymes.
[src:base-editing/apobec] Many of the APOBEC protein features are described in the widely studied APOBEC3G's page.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The development of CRISPR gene editing in 2015 improved the efficiency, specificity, and practicality of large-scale genome editing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Since 2015, genome editing has been experimentally investigated on non-viable human embryos.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In 2019, the first humans were born from genome-edited embryos using the CRISPR technique, as a result of the controversial He Jiankui affair.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Genome editing was pioneered in the 1990s, before the advent of the common current nuclease-based gene-editing platforms, but its use was limited by low efficiencies of editing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Genome editing with engineered nucleases, i.e. all three major classes of these enzymes—zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs), transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs) and engineered meganucleases—were selected by *Nature Methods* as the 2011 Method of the Year.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The CRISPR-Cas system was selected by *Science* as 2015 Breakthrough of the Year.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] As of 2015, four families of engineered nucleases were used: meganucleases, zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs), transcription activator-like effector-based nucleases (TALEN), and the clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats (CRISPR/Cas9) system.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Nine genome editors were available as of 2017.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In 2018, the common methods for such editing used engineered nucleases, or "molecular scissors".
[src:base-editing/base-editing] These nucleases create site-specific double-strand breaks (DSBs) at desired locations in the genome.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The induced double-strand breaks are repaired through nonhomologous end-joining (NHEJ) or homologous recombination (HR), resulting in targeted mutations ('edits').
[src:base-editing/base-editing] A cautionary perspective on the possible blind spots and risks of CRISPR and related biotechnologies has been recently discussed, focusing on the stochastic nature of cellular control processes.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The University of Edinburgh Roslin Institute engineered pigs resistant to a virus that causes porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome, which costs US and European pig farmers $2.6 billion annually.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In February 2020, a US trial safely showed CRISPR gene editing on 3 cancer patients.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In 2020 Sicilian Rouge High GABA, a tomato that makes more of an amino acid said to promote relaxation, was approved for sale in Japan.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In 2021, England (not the rest of the UK) planned to remove restrictions on gene-edited plants and animals, moving from European Union-compliant regulation to rules closer to those of the US and some other countries.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] An April 2021 European Commission report found "strong indications" that the current regulatory regime was not appropriate for gene editing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Later in 2021, researchers announced a CRISPR alternative, labelled obligate mobile element–guided activity (OMEGA) proteins including IscB, IsrB and TnpB as endonucleases found in transposons, and guided by small ωRNAs.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Genetic engineering, as method of introducing new genetic elements into organisms, has been around since the 1970s.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] One drawback of this technology has been the random nature with which the DNA is inserted into the host's genome, which can impair or alter other genes within the organism.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] However, several methods have been discovered that target the inserted genes to specific sites within an organism's genome.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It has also enabled the editing of specific sequences within a genome, as well as reduced off-target effects.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This could be used for research purposes, by targeting mutations to specific genes, and in gene therapy.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] By inserting a functional gene into an organism, and targeting it to replace the defective one, it could be possible to cure certain genetic diseases.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Early methods to target genes to certain sites within a genome of an organism (called gene targeting) relied on homologous recombination (HR).
[src:base-editing/base-editing] By creating DNA constructs that contain a template that matches the targeted genome sequence, it is possible that the HR processes within the cell will insert the construct at the desired location.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Using this method on embryonic stem cells led to the development of transgenic mice with targeted genes knocked out.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It has also been possible to knock in genes or alter gene expression patterns.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In recognition of their discovery of how homologous recombination can be used to introduce genetic modifications in mice through embryonic stem cells, Mario Capecchi, Martin Evans and Oliver Smithies were awarded the 2007 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] If a vital gene is knocked out, it can prove lethal to the organism.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In order to study the function of these genes, site specific recombinases (SSR) were used.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The two most common types are the Cre-LoxP and Flp-FRT systems.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Cre recombinase is an enzyme that removes DNA by homologous recombination between binding sequences known as Lox-P sites.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The Flip-FRT system operates in a similar way, with the Flip recombinase recognising FRT sequences.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] By crossing an organism containing the recombinase sites flanking the gene of interest with an organism that express the SSR under control of tissue specific promoters, it is possible to knock out or switch on genes only in certain cells.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] These techniques were also used to remove marker genes from transgenic animals.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Further modifications of these systems allowed researchers to induce recombination only under certain conditions, allowing genes to be knocked out or expressed at desired times or stages of development.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] A common form of genome editing relies on the concept of DNA double stranded break (DSB) repair mechanics.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] There are two major pathways that repair DSB; non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) and homology directed repair (HDR).
[src:base-editing/base-editing] NHEJ uses a variety of enzymes to directly join the DNA ends, while the more accurate HDR uses a homologous sequence as a template for regeneration of missing DNA sequences at the break point.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This can be exploited by creating a vector with the desired genetic elements within a sequence that is homologous to the flanking sequences of a DSB.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This will result in the desired change being inserted at the site of the DSB.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] While HDR based gene editing is similar to the homologous recombination based gene targeting, the rate of recombination is increased by at least three orders of magnitude.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The key to genome editing is creating a DSB at a specific point within the genome.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Commonly used restriction enzymes are effective at cutting DNA, but generally recognize and cut at multiple sites.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] To overcome this challenge and create site-specific DSB, three distinct classes of nucleases have been discovered and bioengineered to date.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] These are the Zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs), transcription-activator like effector nucleases (TALEN), meganucleases and the clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats (CRISPR/Cas9) system.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Meganucleases, discovered in the late 1980s, are enzymes in the endonuclease family which are characterized by their capacity to recognize and cut large DNA sequences (from 14 to 40 base pairs).
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The most widespread and best known meganucleases are the proteins in the LAGLIDADG family, which owe their name to a conserved amino acid sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Meganucleases, found commonly in microbial species, have the unique property of having very long recognition sequences (>14bp) thus making them naturally very specific.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] However, there is virtually no chance of finding the exact meganuclease required to act on a chosen specific DNA sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] To overcome this challenge, mutagenesis and high throughput screening methods have been used to create meganuclease variants that recognize unique sequences.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Others have been able to fuse various meganucleases and create hybrid enzymes that recognize a new sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Yet others have attempted to alter the DNA interacting aminoacids of the meganuclease to design sequence specific meganucleases in a method named rationally designed meganuclease.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Another approach involves using computer models to try to predict as accurately as possible the activity of the modified meganucleases and the specificity of the recognized nucleic sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] A large bank containing several tens of thousands of protein units has been created.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] As opposed to meganucleases, the concept behind ZFNs and TALEN technology is based on a non-specific DNA cutting catalytic domain, which can then be linked to specific DNA sequence recognizing peptides such as zinc fingers and transcription activator-like effectors (TALEs).
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The first step to this was to find an endonuclease whose DNA recognition site and cleaving site were separate from each other, a situation that is not the most common among restriction enzymes.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Once this enzyme was found, its cleaving portion could be separated which would be very non-specific as it would have no recognition ability.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This portion could then be linked to sequence recognizing peptides that could lead to very high specificity.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Zinc finger motifs occur in several transcription factors.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The zinc ion, found in 8% of all human proteins, plays an important role in the organization of their three-dimensional structure.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In transcription factors, it is most often located at the protein-DNA interaction sites, where it stabilizes the motif.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The C-terminal part of each finger is responsible for the specific recognition of the DNA sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The recognized sequences are short, made up of around 3 base pairs, but by combining 6 to 8 zinc fingers whose recognition sites have been characterized, it is possible to obtain specific proteins for sequences of around 20 base pairs.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It is therefore possible to control the expression of a specific gene.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It has been demonstrated that this strategy can be used to promote a process of angiogenesis in animals.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It is also possible to fuse a protein constructed in this way with the catalytic domain of an endonuclease in order to induce a targeted DNA break, and therefore to use these proteins as genome engineering tools.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The method generally adopted for this involves associating two DNA binding proteins – each containing 3 to 6 specifically chosen zinc fingers – with the catalytic domain of the FokI endonuclease which need to dimerize to cleave the double-strand DNA.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The two proteins recognize two DNA sequences that are a few nucleotides apart.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Linking the two zinc finger proteins to their respective sequences brings the two FokI domains closer together.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] FokI requires dimerization to have nuclease activity and this means the specificity increases dramatically as each nuclease partner would recognize a unique DNA sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] To enhance this effect, FokI nucleases have been engineered that can only function as heterodimers.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Several approaches are used to design specific zinc finger nucleases for the chosen sequences.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The most widespread involves combining zinc-finger units with known specificities (modular assembly).
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Various selection techniques, using bacteria, yeast or mammal cells have been developed to identify the combinations that offer the best specificity and the best cell tolerance.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The heterodimer functioning nucleases would avoid the possibility of unwanted homodimer activity and thus increase specificity of the DSB.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Although the nuclease portions of both ZFNs and TALEN constructs have similar properties, the difference between these engineered nucleases is in their DNA recognition peptide.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] ZFNs rely on Cys2-His2 zinc fingers and TALEN constructs on TALEs.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Both of these DNA recognizing peptide domains have the characteristic that they are naturally found in combinations in their proteins.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Cys2-His2 Zinc fingers typically happen in repeats that are 3 bp apart and are found in diverse combinations in a variety of nucleic acid interacting proteins such as transcription factors.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Each finger of the Zinc finger domain is completely independent and the binding capacity of one finger is impacted by its neighbor.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] TALEs on the other hand are found in repeats with a one-to-one recognition ratio between the amino acids and the recognized nucleotide pairs.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Because both zinc fingers and TALEs happen in repeated patterns, different combinations can be tried to create a wide variety of sequence specificities.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Zinc finger nucleases are research and development tools that have already been used to modify a range of genomes, in particular by the laboratories in the Zinc Finger Consortium.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The US company Sangamo BioSciences uses zinc finger nucleases to carry out research into the genetic engineering of stem cells and the modification of immune cells for therapeutic purposes.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Modified T lymphocytes are currently undergoing phase I clinical trials to treat a type of brain tumor (glioblastoma) and in the fight against AIDS.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs) are specific DNA-binding proteins that feature an array of 33 or 34-amino acid repeats.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] TALENs are artificial restriction enzymes designed by fusing the DNA cutting domain of a nuclease to TALE domains, which can be tailored to specifically recognize a unique DNA sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] These fusion proteins serve as readily targetable "DNA scissors" for gene editing applications that enable to perform targeted genome modifications such as sequence insertion, deletion, repair and replacement in living cells.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The nuclease can create double strand breaks at the target site that can be repaired by error-prone non-homologous end-joining (NHEJ), resulting in gene disruptions through the introduction of small insertions or deletions.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Each repeat is conserved, with the exception of the so-called repeat variable di-residues (RVDs) at amino acid positions 12 and 13.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The RVDs determine the DNA sequence to which the TALE will bind.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This simple one-to-one correspondence between the TALE repeats and the corresponding DNA sequence makes the process of assembling repeat arrays to recognize novel DNA sequences straightforward.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] These TALEs can be fused to the catalytic domain from a DNA nuclease, FokI, to generate a transcription activator-like effector nuclease (TALEN).
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The resultant TALEN constructs combine specificity and activity, effectively generating engineered sequence-specific nucleases that bind and cleave DNA sequences only at pre-selected sites.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The TALEN target recognition system is based on an easy-to-predict code.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] TAL nucleases are specific to their target due in part to the length of their 30+ base pairs binding site.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] TALEN can be performed within a 6 base pairs range of any single nucleotide in the entire genome.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] TALEN constructs are used in a similar way to designed zinc finger nucleases, and have three advantages in targeted mutagenesis: (1) DNA binding specificity is higher, (2) off-target effects are lower, and (3) construction of DNA-binding domains is easier.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] CRISPRs (Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) are genetic elements that bacteria use as a kind of acquired immunity to protect against viruses.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] They consist of short sequences that originate from viral genomes and have been incorporated into the bacterial genome.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Cas (CRISPR associated proteins) process these sequences and cut matching viral DNA sequences.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] By introducing plasmids containing Cas genes and specifically constructed CRISPRs into eukaryotic cells, the eukaryotic genome can be cut at any desired position.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Larger modifications used to be inefficient and error-prone but recent developments allow fairly reliable larger modifications.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] For instance, the quadruple pegRNA strategy (QuadPE) allowed researchers to stably insert large DNA fragments into human cells ranging from 1.6 to 26 kb at an efficiency of about 40%.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] One of the earliest methods of efficiently editing nucleic acids employs nucleobase modifying enzymes directed by nucleic acid guide sequences.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It was first described in the 1990s and has seen a resurgence more recently.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This method has the advantage that it does not require breaking the genomic DNA strands, and thus avoids the random insertions and deletions associated with DNA strand breakage.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It is only appropriate for precise editing requiring single nucleotide changes and has found to be highly efficient for this type of editing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] ARCUT stands for artificial restriction DNA cutter, it is a technique developed by Makoto Komiyama.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This method uses pseudo-complementary peptide nucleic acid (pcPNA), for identifying cleavage site within the chromosome.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Once pcPNA specifies the site, excision is carried out by cerium (CE) and EDTA (chemical mixture), which performs the splicing function.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Meganucleases method of gene editing is the least efficient of the methods mentioned above.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Due to the nature of its DNA-binding element and the cleaving element, it is limited to recognizing one potential target every 1,000 nucleotides.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] ZFN was developed to overcome the limitations of meganuclease.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The number of possible targets ZFN can recognise was increased to one in every 140 nucleotides.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] However, both methods are unpredictable because of their DNA-binding elements affecting each other.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] As a result, high degrees of expertise and lengthy and costly validation processes are required.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] TALE nucleases, being the most precise and specific method, yields a higher efficiency than the previous two methods.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It achieves such efficiency because the DNA-binding element consists of an array of TALE subunits, each of them having the capability of recognizing a specific DNA nucleotide chain independently from others, resulting in a higher number of target sites with high precision.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] New TALE nucleases take about one week and a few hundred dollars to create, with specific expertise in molecular biology and protein engineering.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] CRISPR nucleases have a slightly lower precision when compared to the TALE nucleases.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This is caused by the need to have a specific nucleotide at one end in order to produce the guide RNA that CRISPR uses to repair the double-strand break it induces.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It has been shown to be the quickest and cheapest method, only costing less than two hundred dollars and a few days of time.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] CRISPR also requires the least amount of expertise in molecular biology, as the design lays in the guide RNA instead of the proteins.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] One major advantage that CRISPR has over the ZFN and TALEN methods is that it can be directed to target different DNA sequences using its ~80nt CRISPR sgRNAs, while both ZFN and TALEN methods required construction and testing of the proteins created for targeting each DNA sequence.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Because off-target activity of an active nuclease would have potentially dangerous consequences at the genetic and organismal levels, the precision of meganucleases, ZFNs, CRISPR, and TALEN-based fusions has been an active area of research.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] While variable figures have been reported, ZFNs tend to have more cytotoxicity than TALEN methods or RNA-guided nucleases, while TALEN and RNA-guided approaches tend to have the greatest efficiency and fewer off-target effects.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Based on the maximum theoretical distance between DNA binding and nuclease activity, TALEN approaches result in the greatest precision.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The methods for scientists and researchers wanting to study genomic diversity and all possible associated phenotypes were very slow, expensive, and inefficient.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Prior to this new revolution, researchers would have to do single-gene manipulations and tweak the genome one little section at a time, observe the phenotype, and start the process over with a different single-gene manipulation.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Therefore, researchers at the Wyss Institute at Harvard University designed the MAGE, a powerful technology that improves the process of in vivo genome editing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It allows for quick and efficient manipulations of a genome, all happening in a machine small enough to put on top of a small kitchen table.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Those mutations combine with the variation that naturally occurs during cell mitosis creating billions of cellular mutations.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Chemically combined, synthetic single-stranded DNA (ssDNA) and a pool of oligonucleotides are introduced at targeted areas of the cell, thereby creating genetic modifications.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The cyclical process involves transformation of ssDNA (by electroporation) followed by outgrowth, during which bacteriophage homologous recombination proteins mediate annealing of ssDNAs to their genomic targets.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Experiments targeting selective phenotypic markers are screened and identified by plating the cells on differential medias.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Each cycle ultimately takes 2.5 hours to process, with additional time required to grow isogenic cultures and characterize mutations.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] By iteratively introducing libraries of mutagenic ssDNAs targeting multiple sites, MAGE can generate combinatorial genetic diversity in a cell population.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] There can be up to 50 genome edits, from single nucleotide base pairs to whole genome or gene networks simultaneously with results in a matter of days.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] MAGE experiments can be divided into three classes, characterized by varying degrees of scale and complexity: (i) many target sites, single genetic mutations; (ii) single target site, many genetic mutations; and (iii) many target sites, many genetic mutations.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] An example of class three was reflected in 2009, where Church and colleagues were able to program *Escherichia coli* to produce five times the normal amount of lycopene, an antioxidant normally found in tomato seeds and linked to anti-cancer properties.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] They applied MAGE to optimize the 1-deoxy-D-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) metabolic pathway in *Escherichia coli* to overproduce isoprenoid lycopene.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It took them about 3 days and just over $1,000 in materials.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The ease, speed, and cost efficiency in which MAGE can alter genomes can transform how industries approach the manufacturing and production of important compounds in the bioengineering, bioenergy, biomedical engineering, synthetic biology, pharmaceutical, agricultural, and chemical industries.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] As of 2012, efficient genome editing had been developed for a wide range of experimental systems ranging from plants to animals, often beyond clinical interest, and was becoming a standard experimental strategy in research labs.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The recent generation of rat, zebrafish, maize and tobacco ZFN-mediated mutants and the improvements in TALEN-based approaches testify to the significance of the methods, and the list is expanding rapidly.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Genome editing with engineered nucleases will likely contribute to many fields of life sciences from studying gene functions in plants and animals to gene therapy in humans.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] For instance, the field of synthetic biology which aims to engineer cells and organisms to perform novel functions, is likely to benefit from the ability of engineered nuclease to add or remove genomic elements and therefore create complex systems.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In addition, gene functions can be studied using stem cells with engineered nucleases.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The combination of recent discoveries in genetic engineering, particularly gene editing and the latest improvement in bovine reproduction technologies (e.g.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] *in vitro* embryo culture) allows for genome editing directly in fertilised oocytes using synthetic highly specific endonucleases.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Furthermore, gene editing can be applied to certain types of fish in aquaculture such as Atlantic salmon.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Gene editing in fish is currently experimental, but the possibilities include growth, disease resistance, sterility, controlled reproduction, and colour.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Selecting for these traits can allow for a more sustainable environment and better welfare for the fish.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] AquAdvantage salmon is a genetically modified Atlantic salmon developed by AquaBounty Technologies.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Thanks to the parallel development of single-cell transcriptomics, genome editing and new stem cell models we are now entering a scientifically exciting period where functional genetics is no longer restricted to animal models but can be performed directly in human samples.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Single-cell gene expression analysis has resolved a transcriptional road-map of human development from which key candidate genes are being identified for functional studies.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Using global transcriptomics data to guide experimentation, the CRISPR based genome editing tool has made it feasible to disrupt or remove key genes in order to elucidate function in a human setting.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Genome editing using Meganuclease, ZFNs, and TALEN provides a new strategy for genetic manipulation in plants and are likely to assist in the engineering of desired plant traits by modifying endogenous genes.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] For instance, site-specific gene addition in major crop species can be used for 'trait stacking' whereby several desired traits are physically linked to ensure their co-segregation during the breeding processes.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Progress in such cases have been recently reported in *Arabidopsis thaliana* and *Zea mays*.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In *Arabidopsis thaliana*, using ZFN-assisted gene targeting, two herbicide-resistant genes (tobacco acetolactate synthase SuRA and SuRB) were introduced to SuR loci with as high as 2% transformed cells with mutations.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In Zea mays, disruption of the target locus was achieved by ZFN-induced DSBs and the resulting NHEJ.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] ZFN was also used to drive herbicide-tolerance gene expression cassette (PAT) into the targeted endogenous locus IPK1 in this case.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Such genome modification observed in the regenerated plants has been shown to be inheritable and was transmitted to the next generation.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In addition, TALEN-based genome engineering has been extensively tested and optimized for use in plants.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Several optimizations need to be made in order to improve editing plant genomes using ZFN-mediated targeting.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] There is a need for reliable design and subsequent test of the nucleases, the absence of toxicity of the nucleases, the appropriate choice of the plant tissue for targeting, the routes of induction of enzyme activity, the lack of off-target mutagenesis, and a reliable detection of mutated cases.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] A common delivery method for CRISPR/Cas9 in plants is *Agrobacterium*-based transformation.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] T-DNA is introduced directly into the plant genome by a T4SS mechanism.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Cas9 and gRNA-based expression cassettes are turned into Ti plasmids, which are transformed in *Agrobacterium* for plant application.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] To improve Cas9 delivery in live plants, viruses are being used more effective transgene delivery.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The ideal gene therapy practice is one that replaces the defective gene with a normal allele at its natural location.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This is advantageous over a virally-delivered gene, as there is no need to include the full coding sequences and regulatory sequences when only a small proportion of the gene needs to be altered, as is often the case.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The expression of the partially replaced genes is also more consistent with normal cell biology than full genes that are carried by viral vectors.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The first clinical use of TALEN-based genome editing was in the treatment of CD19+ acute lymphoblastic leukemia in an 11-month old child in 2015.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Modified donor T cells were engineered to attack the leukemia cells, to be resistant to Alemtuzumab, and to evade detection by the host immune system after introduction.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Extensive research has been done in cells and animals using CRISPR-Cas9 to attempt to correct genetic mutations which cause genetic diseases such as Down syndrome, spina bifida, anencephaly, and Turner and Klinefelter syndromes.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In February 2019, medical scientists working with Sangamo Therapeutics, headquartered in Richmond, California, announced the first ever "in body" human gene editing therapy to permanently alter DNA - in a patient with Hunter syndrome.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Clinical trials by Sangamo involving gene editing using Zinc Finger Nuclease (ZFN) are ongoing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Researchers have used CRISPR-Cas9 gene drives to modify genes associated with sterility in *A. gambiae*, the vector for malaria.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This technique has further implications in eradicating other vector borne diseases such as yellow fever, dengue, and Zika.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The CRISPR-Cas9 system can be programmed to modulate the population of any bacterial species by targeting clinical genotypes or epidemiological isolates.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] It can selectively enable the beneficial bacterial species over the harmful ones by eliminating pathogen, which gives it an advantage over broad-spectrum antibiotics.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Antiviral applications for therapies targeting human viruses such as HIV, herpes, and hepatitis B virus are under research.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] CRISPR can be used to target the virus or the host to disrupt genes encoding the virus cell-surface receptor proteins.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In November 2018, He Jiankui announced that he had edited two human embryos, to attempt to disable the gene for CCR5, which codes for a receptor that HIV uses to enter cells.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] He said that twin girls, Lulu and Nana, had been born a few weeks earlier.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] He said that the girls still carried functional copies of CCR5 along with disabled CCR5 (mosaicism) and were still vulnerable to HIV.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The work was widely condemned as unethical, dangerous, and premature.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The monkey clones were made in order to study several medical diseases.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In the future, an important goal of research into genome editing with engineered nucleases must be the improvement of the safety and specificity of the nucleases action.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] For example, improving the ability to detect off-target events can improve our ability to learn about ways of preventing them.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In addition, zinc-fingers used in ZFNs are seldom completely specific, and some may cause a toxic reaction.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] However, the toxicity has been reported to be reduced by modifications done on the cleavage domain of the ZFN.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In addition, research by Dana Carroll into modifying the genome with engineered nucleases has shown the need for better understanding of the basic recombination and repair machinery of DNA.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In the future, a possible method to identify secondary targets would be to capture broken ends from cells expressing the ZFNs and to sequence the flanking DNA using high-throughput sequencing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Because of the ease of use and cost-efficiency of CRISPR, extensive research is currently being done on it.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] There are now more publications on CRISPR than ZFN and TALEN despite how recent the discovery of CRISPR is.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Both CRISPR and TALEN are favored to be the choices to be implemented in large-scale productions due to their precision and efficiency.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Genome editing occurs also as a natural process without artificial genetic engineering.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The agents that are competent to edit genetic codes are viruses or subviral RNA-agents.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Although DNA has higher efficiency than many other methods in reverse genetics, it is still not highly efficient; in many cases less than half of the treated populations obtain the desired changes.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] For example, when one is planning to use the cell's NHEJ to create a mutation, the cell's HDR systems will also be at work correcting the DSB with lower mutational rates.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Traditionally, mice have been the most common choice for researchers as a host of a disease model.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] CRISPR can help bridge the gap between this model and human clinical trials by creating transgenic disease models in larger animals such as pigs, dogs, and non-human primates.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Using the CRISPR-Cas9 system, the programmed Cas9 protein and the sgRNA can be directly introduced into fertilized zygotes to achieve the desired gene modifications when creating transgenic models in rodents.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] This allows bypassing of the usual cell targeting stage in generating transgenic lines, and as a result, it reduces generation time by 90%.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] One potential that CRISPR brings with its effectiveness is the application of xenotransplantation.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In previous research trials, CRISPR demonstrated the ability to target and eliminate endogenous retroviruses, which reduces the risk of transmitting diseases and reduces immune barriers.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Eliminating these problems improves donor organ function, which brings this application closer to a reality.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In plants, genome editing is seen as a viable solution to the conservation of biodiversity.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Gene drive are a potential tool to alter the reproductive rate of invasive species, although there are significant associated risks.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Many transhumanists see genome editing as a potential tool for human enhancement.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Australian biologist and Professor of Genetics David Andrew Sinclair notes that "the new technologies with genome editing will allow it to be used on individuals (...) to have (...) healthier children" – designer babies.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] According to a September 2016 report by the Nuffield Council on Bioethics in the future it may be possible to enhance people with genes from other organisms or wholly synthetic genes to for example improve night vision and sense of smell.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The American National Academy of Sciences and National Academy of Medicine issued a report in February 2017 giving qualified support to human genome editing.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In the 2016 *Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community* statement United States Director of National Intelligence, James R.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Clapper, named genome editing as a potential weapon of mass destruction, stating that genome editing conducted by countries with regulatory or ethical standards "different from Western countries" probably increases the risk of the creation of harmful biological agents or products.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] According to the statement the broad distribution, low cost, and accelerated pace of development of this technology, its deliberate or unintentional misuse might lead to far-reaching economic and national security implications.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] For instance, technologies such as CRISPR could be used to make "killer mosquitoes", cause plagues that wipe out staple crops, or create highly deadly viruses.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] According to a September 2016 report by the Nuffield Council on Bioethics, the simplicity and low cost of tools to edit the genetic code will allow amateurs – or "biohackers" – to perform their own experiments, posing a potential risk from the release of genetically modified bugs.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] The review also found that the risks and benefits of modifying a person's genome – and having those changes pass on to future generations – are so complex that they demand urgent ethical scrutiny.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Such modifications might have unintended consequences which could harm not only the child, but also their future children, as the altered gene would be in their sperm or eggs.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] Furthermore, there are additional concerns about the ecological risks of releasing gene drives into wild populations.
[src:base-editing/base-editing] In 2020, the Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Emmanuelle Charpentier and Jennifer Doudna for "the development of a method for genome editing".
[src:base-editing/deaminase] In the human body, deamination takes place primarily in the liver; however, it can also occur in the kidney.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] In situations of excess protein intake, deamination is used to break down amino acids for energy.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] The amino group is removed from the amino acid and converted to ammonia.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] The rest of the amino acid is made up of mostly carbon and hydrogen, and is recycled or oxidized for energy.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Ammonia is toxic to the human system, and enzymes convert it to urea or uric acid by addition of carbon dioxide molecules (which is not considered a deamination process) in the urea cycle, which also takes place in the liver.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Urea and uric acid can safely diffuse into the blood and then be excreted in urine.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Spontaneous deamination is the hydrolysis reaction of cytosine into uracil, releasing ammonia in the process.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] This can occur in vitro through the use of bisulfite, which deaminates cytosine, but not 5-methylcytosine.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] This property has allowed researchers to sequence methylated DNA to distinguish non-methylated cytosine (shown up as uracil) and methylated cytosine (unaltered).
[src:base-editing/deaminase] In DNA, this spontaneous deamination is corrected for by the removal of uracil (product of cytosine deamination and *not* part of DNA) by uracil-DNA glycosylase, generating an abasic (AP) site.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] The resulting abasic site is then recognised by enzymes (AP endonucleases) that break a phosphodiester bond in the DNA, permitting the repair of the resulting lesion by replacement with another cytosine.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] A DNA polymerase may perform this replacement via nick translation, a terminal excision reaction by its 5'⟶3' exonuclease activity, followed by a fill-in reaction by its polymerase activity.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] DNA ligase then forms a phosphodiester bond to seal the resulting nicked duplex product, which now includes a new, correct cytosine (Base excision repair).
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Spontaneous deamination of 5-methylcytosine results in thymine and ammonia.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] This is the most common single nucleotide mutation.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] In DNA, this reaction, if detected prior to passage of the replication fork, can be corrected by the enzyme thymine-DNA glycosylase, which removes the thymine base in a G/T mismatch.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] This leaves an abasic site that is repaired by AP endonucleases and polymerase, as with uracil-DNA glycosylase.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] A known result of cytosine methylation is the increase of C-to-T transition mutations through the process of deamination.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Cytosine deamination can alter the genome's many regulatory functions; previously silenced transposable elements (TEs) may become transcriptionally active due to the loss of CPG sites.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] TEs have been proposed to accelerate the mechanism of enhancer creation by providing extra DNA that is compatible with the host transcription factors that eventually have an impact on C-to-T mutations.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Deamination of guanine results in the formation of xanthine.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Xanthine, however, still pairs with cytosine.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Deamination of adenine results in the formation of hypoxanthine.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] Hypoxanthine, in a manner analogous to the imine tautomer of adenine, selectively base pairs with cytosine instead of thymine.
[src:base-editing/deaminase] This results in a post-replicative transition mutation, where the original A-T base pair transforms into a G-C base pair.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A **point mutation** is a genetic mutation where a single nucleotide base is changed, inserted or deleted from a DNA or RNA sequence of an organism's genome.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point mutations have a variety of effects on the downstream protein product—consequences that are moderately predictable based upon the specifics of the mutation.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] These consequences can range from no effect (e.g. synonymous mutations) to deleterious effects (e.g. frameshift mutations), with regard to protein production, composition, and function.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point mutations usually take place during DNA replication.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] DNA replication occurs when one double-stranded DNA molecule creates two single strands of DNA, each of which is a template for the creation of the complementary strand.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A single point mutation can change the whole DNA sequence.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Changing one purine or pyrimidine may change the amino acid that the nucleotides code for.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point mutations may arise from spontaneous mutations that occur during DNA replication.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The rate of mutation may be increased by mutagens.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Mutagens can be physical, such as radiation from UV rays, X-rays or extreme heat, or chemical (molecules that misplace base pairs or disrupt the helical shape of DNA).
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Mutagens associated with cancers are often studied to learn about cancer and its prevention.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] There are multiple ways for point mutations to occur.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] First, ultraviolet (UV) light and higher-frequency light have ionizing capability, which in turn can affect DNA.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Reactive oxygen molecules with free radicals, which are a byproduct of cellular metabolism, can also be very harmful to DNA.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] These reactants can lead to both single-stranded and double-stranded DNA breaks.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Third, bonds in DNA eventually degrade, which creates another problem to keep the integrity of DNA to a high standard.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] There can also be replication errors that lead to substitution, insertion, or deletion mutations.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In 1959 Ernst Freese coined the terms "transitions" or "transversions" to categorize different types of point mutations.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Transitions are replacement of a purine base with another purine or replacement of a pyrimidine with another pyrimidine.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Transversions are replacement of a purine with a pyrimidine or vice versa.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] There is a systematic difference in mutation rates for transitions (Alpha) and transversions (Beta).
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Transition mutations are about ten times more common than transversions.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Nonsense mutations include stop-gain and start-loss.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Stop-gain is a mutation that results in a premature termination codon (*a stop was gained*), which signals the end of translation.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This interruption causes the protein to be abnormally shortened.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The number of amino acids lost mediates the impact on the protein's functionality and whether it will function whatsoever.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Stop-loss is a mutation in the original termination codon (*a stop was lost*), resulting in abnormal extension of a protein's carboxyl terminus.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Start-gain creates an AUG start codon upstream of the original start site.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] If the new AUG is near the original start site, in-frame within the processed transcript and downstream to a ribosomal binding site, it can be used to initiate translation.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The likely effect is additional amino acids added to the amino terminus of the original protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Frame-shift mutations are also possible in start-gain mutations, but typically do not affect translation of the original protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Start-loss is a point mutation in a transcript's AUG start codon, resulting in the reduction or elimination of protein production.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Missense mutations code for a different amino acid.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A missense mutation changes a codon so that a different protein is created, a non-synonymous change.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Conservative mutations result in an amino acid change.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] However, the properties of the amino acid remain the same (e.g., hydrophobic, hydrophilic, etc.) At times, a change to one amino acid in the protein is not detrimental to the organism as a whole.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Most proteins can withstand one or two point mutations before their function changes.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Non-conservative mutations result in an amino acid change that has different properties than the wild type.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The protein may lose its function, which can result in a disease in the organism.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] For example, sickle-cell disease is caused by a single point mutation (a missense mutation) in the beta-hemoglobin gene that converts a GAG codon into GUG, which encodes the amino acid valine rather than glutamic acid.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The protein may also exhibit a "gain of function" or become activated, such is the case with the mutation changing a valine to glutamic acid in the BRAF gene; this leads to an activation of the RAF protein which causes unlimited proliferative signalling in cancer cells.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] These are both examples of a non-conservative (missense) mutation.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Silent mutations code for the same amino acid (a "synonymous substitution").
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A silent mutation does not affect the functioning of the protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A single nucleotide can change, but the new codon specifies the same amino acid, resulting in an unmutated protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This type of change is called synonymous change since the old and new codon code for the same amino acid.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This is possible because 64 codons specify only 20 amino acids.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Different codons can lead to differential protein expression levels, however.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Sometimes the term *point mutation* is used to describe insertions or deletions of a single base pair (which has more of an adverse effect on the synthesized protein due to the nucleotides' still being read in triplets, but in different frames: a mutation called a frameshift mutation).
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point mutations that occur in non-coding sequences are most often without consequences, although there are exceptions.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] If the mutated base pair is in the promoter sequence of a gene, then the expression of the gene may change.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Also, if the mutation occurs in the splicing site of an intron, then this may interfere with correct splicing of the transcribed pre-mRNA.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] By altering just one amino acid, the entire peptide may change, thereby changing the entire protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The new protein is called a protein variant.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] If the original protein functions in cellular reproduction then this single point mutation can change the entire process of cellular reproduction for this organism.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point germline mutations can lead to beneficial as well as harmful traits or diseases.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This leads to adaptations based on the environment where the organism lives.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] An advantageous mutation can create an advantage for that organism and lead to the trait's being passed down from generation to generation, improving and benefiting the entire population.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The scientific theory of evolution is greatly dependent on point mutations in cells.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The theory explains the diversity and history of living organisms on Earth.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In relation to point mutations, it states that beneficial mutations allow the organism to thrive and reproduce, thereby passing its positively affected mutated genes on to the next generation.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] On the other hand, harmful mutations cause the organism to die or be less likely to reproduce in a phenomenon known as natural selection.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] There are different short-term and long-term effects that can arise from mutations.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Smaller ones would be a halting of the cell cycle at numerous points.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This means that a codon coding for the amino acid glycine may be changed to a stop codon, causing the proteins that should have been produced to be deformed and unable to complete their intended tasks.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Because the mutations can affect the DNA and thus the chromatin, it can prohibit mitosis from occurring due to the lack of a complete chromosome.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Problems can also arise during the processes of transcription and replication of DNA.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] These all prohibit the cell from reproduction and thus lead to the death of the cell.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Long-term effects can be a permanent changing of a chromosome, which can lead to a mutation.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] These mutations can be either beneficial or detrimental.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Cancer is an example of how they can be detrimental.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Other effects of point mutations, or single nucleotide polymorphisms in DNA, depend on the location of the mutation within the gene.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] For example, if the mutation occurs in the region of the gene responsible for coding, the amino acid sequence of the encoded protein may be altered, causing a change in the function, protein localization, stability of the protein or protein complex.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Many methods have been proposed to predict the effects of missense mutations on proteins.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] While majority of methods provide a binary classification of effects of mutations into damaging and benign, a new level of annotation is needed to offer an explanation of why and how these mutations damage proteins.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Moreover, if the mutation occurs in the region of the gene where transcriptional machinery binds to the protein, the mutation can affect the binding of the transcription factors because the short nucleotide sequences recognized by the transcription factors will be altered.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Mutations in this region can affect rate of efficiency of gene transcription, which in turn can alter levels of mRNA and, thus, protein levels in general.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point mutations can have several effects on the behavior and reproduction of a protein depending on where the mutation occurs in the amino acid sequence of the protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] If the mutation occurs in the region of the gene that is responsible for coding for the protein, the amino acid may be altered.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This slight change in the sequence of amino acids can cause a change in the function, activation of the protein meaning how it binds with a given enzyme, where the protein will be located within the cell, or the amount of free energy stored within the protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] If the mutation occurs in the region of the gene where transcriptional machinery binds to the protein, the mutation can affect the way in which transcription factors bind to the protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The mechanisms of transcription bind to a protein through recognition of short nucleotide sequences.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A mutation in this region may alter these sequences and, thus, change the way the transcription factors bind to the protein.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Mutations in this region can affect the efficiency of gene transcription, which controls both the levels of mRNA and overall protein levels.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point mutations—single‑base changes in the DNA sequence—are one of the most common molecular causes of human disease.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] By altering a single nucleotide, these mutations can substitute one amino acid for another, introduce premature stop codons, or disrupt normal splicing signals.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Depending on where they occur and how they affect the encoded protein, point mutations may abolish enzyme activity, destabilize structural domains, or impair regulatory interactions.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In many inherited disorders, a single missense or nonsense substitution is enough to trigger a cascade of biochemical failures, leading to early‐onset or lifelong symptoms.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In cancer, somatic point mutations can inactivate tumor suppressors or hyperactivate oncogenes, fueling uncontrolled cell growth.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Across the human genetic landscape, thousands of point‐mutation–driven conditions have been cataloged—from relatively common disorders like sickle‐cell anemia and cystic fibrosis to extremely rare syndromes that affect only a handful of families worldwide.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Although each disease has its own pathophysiological details, they share a unifying theme: a precisely localized change in the gene sequence can compromise protein function in a way that no larger chromosomal rearrangement or copy‐number alteration could.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Because point mutations are often amenable to targeted genetic testing, they also highlight how molecular diagnosis and personalized therapies (e.g., small molecules that stabilize a mutant enzyme) rely on knowing exactly which codon is altered.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Although the following examples illustrate the diversity of point-mutation–mediated disorders, there are over 300,000 such mutations recorded in HGMD and over 1,000,000 variants in ClinVar, reflecting the vast spectrum of human point mutations.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Point mutations in multiple tumor suppressor proteins cause cancer.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] For instance, point mutations in Adenomatous Polyposis Coli promote tumorigenesis.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A novel assay, Fast parallel proteolysis (FASTpp), might help swift screening of specific stability defects in individual cancer patients.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Neurofibromatosis is caused by point mutations in the Neurofibromin 1 or Neurofibromin 2 gene.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Sickle-cell anemia is caused by a point mutation in the β-globin chain of hemoglobin, causing the hydrophilic amino acid glutamic acid to be replaced with the hydrophobic amino acid valine at the sixth position.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The β-globin gene is found on the short arm of chromosome 11.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The association of two wild-type α-globin subunits with two mutant β-globin subunits forms hemoglobin S (HbS).
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Under low-oxygen conditions (being at high altitude, for example), the absence of a polar amino acid at position six of the β-globin chain promotes the non-covalent polymerisation (aggregation) of hemoglobin, which distorts red blood cells into a sickle shape and decreases their elasticity.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Hemoglobin is a protein found in red blood cells, and is responsible for the transportation of oxygen through the body.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] There are two subunits that make up the hemoglobin protein: beta-globins and alpha-globins.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Beta-hemoglobin is created from the genetic information on the HBB, or "hemoglobin, beta" gene found on chromosome 11p15.5.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A single point mutation in this polypeptide chain, which is 147 amino acids long, results in the disease known as Sickle Cell Anemia.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Sickle-cell anemia is an autosomal recessive disorder that affects 1 in 500 African Americans, and is one of the most common blood disorders in the United States.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The single replacement of the sixth amino acid in the beta-globin, glutamic acid, with valine results in deformed red blood cells.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] These sickle-shaped cells cannot carry nearly as much oxygen as normal red blood cells and they get caught more easily in the capillaries, cutting off blood supply to vital organs.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The single nucleotide change in the beta-globin means that even the smallest of exertions on the part of the carrier results in severe pain and even heart attack.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Below is a chart depicting the first thirteen amino acids in the normal and abnormal sickle cell polypeptide chain.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The cause of Tay–Sachs disease is a genetic defect that is passed from parent to child.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This genetic defect is located in the HEXA gene, which is found on chromosome 15.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The HEXA gene makes part of an enzyme called beta-hexosaminidase A, which plays a critical role in the nervous system.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This enzyme helps break down a fatty substance called GM2 ganglioside in nerve cells.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Mutations in the HEXA gene disrupt the activity of beta-hexosaminidase A, preventing the breakdown of the fatty substances.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] As a result, the fatty substances accumulate to deadly levels in the brain and spinal cord.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The buildup of GM2 ganglioside causes progressive damage to the nerve cells.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This is the cause of the signs and symptoms of Tay-Sachs disease.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In molecular biology, **repeat-induced point mutation** or **RIP** is a process by which DNA accumulates G:C to A:T transition mutations.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In *Neurospora crassa*, sequences mutated by RIP are often methylated *de novo*.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] RIP occurs during the sexual stage in haploid nuclei after fertilization but prior to meiotic DNA replication.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In *Neurospora crassa*, repeat sequences of at least 400 base pairs in length are vulnerable to RIP.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Repeats with as low as 80% nucleotide identity may also be subject to RIP.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Though the exact mechanism of repeat recognition and mutagenesis are poorly understood, RIP results in repeated sequences undergoing multiple transition mutations.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The RIP mutations do not seem to be limited to repeated sequences.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Indeed, for example, in the phytopathogenic fungus *L. maculans*, RIP mutations are found in single copy regions, adjacent to the repeated elements.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] These regions are either non-coding regions or genes encoding small secreted proteins including avirulence genes.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The degree of RIP within these single copy regions was proportional to their proximity to repetitive elements.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Rep and Kistler have speculated that the presence of highly repetitive regions containing transposons, may promote mutation of resident effector genes.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] So the presence of effector genes within such regions is suggested to promote their adaptation and diversification when exposed to strong selection pressure.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] As RIP mutation is traditionally observed to be restricted to repetitive regions and not single copy regions, Fudal *et al.* suggested that leakage of RIP mutation might occur within a relatively short distance of a RIP-affected repeat.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Indeed, this has been reported in *N. crassa* whereby leakage of RIP was detected in single copy sequences at least 930 bp from the boundary of neighbouring duplicated sequences.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] To elucidate the mechanism of detection of repeated sequences leading to RIP may allow to understand how the flanking sequences may also be affected.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] RIP causes G:C to A:T transition mutations within repeats, however, the mechanism that detects the repeated sequences is unknown.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] RID is the only known protein essential for RIP.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] It is a DNA methyltransferease-like protein, that when mutated or knocked out results in loss of RIP.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Deletion of the *rid* homolog in *Aspergillus nidulans*, *dmtA*, results in loss of fertility while deletion of the *rid* homolog in *Ascobolus immersens*, *masc1*, results in fertility defects and loss of methylation induced premeiotically (MIP).
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] RIP is believed to have evolved as a defense mechanism against transposable elements, which resemble parasites by invading and multiplying within the genome.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] RIP creates multiple missense and nonsense mutations in the coding sequence.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This hypermutation of G-C to A-T in repetitive sequences eliminates functional gene products of the sequence (if there were any to begin with).
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] In addition, many of the C-bearing nucleotides become methylated, thus decreasing transcription.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Because RIP is so efficient at detecting and mutating repeats, biologists working on *Neurospora crassa* have used it as a tool for mutagenesis.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] A second copy of a single-copy gene is first transformed into the genome.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The fungus must then mate and go through its sexual cycle to activate the RIP machinery.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Many different mutations within the duplicated gene are obtained from even a single fertilization event so that inactivated alleles, usually due to nonsense mutations, as well as alleles containing missense mutations can be obtained.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The cellular reproduction process of meiosis was discovered by Oscar Hertwig in 1876.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Mitosis was discovered several years later in 1882 by Walther Flemming.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Hertwig studied sea urchins, and noticed that each egg contained one nucleus prior to fertilization and two nuclei after.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] This discovery proved that one spermatozoon could fertilize an egg, and therefore proved the process of meiosis.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Hermann Fol continued Hertwig's research by testing the effects of injecting several spermatozoa into an egg, and found that the process did not work with more than one spermatozoon.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Flemming began his research of cell division starting in 1868.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] The study of cells was an increasingly popular topic in this time period.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] By 1873, Schneider had already begun to describe the steps of cell division.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Flemming furthered this description in 1874 and 1875 as he explained the steps in more detail.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] He also argued with Schneider's findings that the nucleus separated into rod-like structures by suggesting that the nucleus actually separated into threads that in turn separated.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Flemming concluded that cells replicate through cell division, to be more specific mitosis.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Matthew Meselson and Franklin Stahl are credited with the discovery of DNA replication.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Watson and Crick acknowledged that the structure of DNA did indicate that there is some form of replicating process.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] However, there was not a lot of research done on this aspect of DNA until after Watson and Crick.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] People considered all possible methods of determining the replication process of DNA, but none were successful until Meselson and Stahl.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Meselson and Stahl introduced a heavy isotope into some DNA and traced its distribution.
[src:base-editing/point-mutation] Through this experiment, Meselson and Stahl were able to prove that DNA reproduces semi-conservatively.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] Transitions can be caused by several mechanisms, including spontaneous deamination and tautomerization.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] Deamination of cytosine produces uracil while deamination of 5-methylcytosine produces thymine.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] Rare tautomeric forms of DNA bases can also mispair during replication without major distortion of the double helix.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] If these base changes and mismatches escape DNA repair mechanisms, they can become fixed as transition mutations.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] Although there are twice as many possible transversions, transitions occur more often in genomes, a pattern known as transition/transversion bias.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] This bias results mainly from molecular structure and selection pressure.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] In coding regions, transitions are more likely than transversions to produce synonymous substitutions.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] Also, transitions are less likely than transversions to cause drastic amino acid changes because of the structure of the genetic code.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] Moreover, some transition-generating base-pair mismatches may cause less distortion to the DNA double helix which may therefore escape repair mechanisms.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] In vertebrate genomes, spontaneous deamination of 5-methylcytosine creates T:G mismatches that become fixed as C→T transitions.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] As a result, methylated CpG dinucleotides are important hotspots for transition mutations.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] This mechanism contributes to the genome-wide depletion of CpG dinucleotides over evolutionary time.
[src:base-editing/transition-genetics] However, CpG islands are an exception because they are often unmethylated and therefore less affected by this mutational process.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] The human gene encodes one of several uracil-DNA glycosylases.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Alternative promoter usage and splicing of this gene leads to two different isoforms: the mitochondrial UNG1 and the nuclear UNG2.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] One important function of uracil-DNA glycosylases is to prevent mutagenesis by eliminating uracil from DNA molecules by cleaving the N-glycosidic bond and initiating the base-excision repair (BER) pathway.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Uracil bases occur from cytosine deamination or misincorporation of dUMP residues.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] After a mutation occurs, the mutagenic threat of uracil propagates through any subsequent DNA replication steps.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Once unzipped, mismatched guanine and uracil pairs are separated, and DNA polymerase inserts complementary bases to form a guanine-cytosine (GC) pair in one daughter strand and an adenine-uracil (AU) pair in the other.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Half of all progeny DNA derived from the mutated template inherit a shift from GC to AU at the mutation site.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] UDG excises uracil in both AU and GU pairs to prevent propagation of the base mismatch to downstream transcription and translation processes.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] With high efficiency and specificity, this glycosylase repairs 100–500 bases damaged daily in the human cell.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Human cells express five to six types of DNA glycosylases, all of which share a common mechanism of base eversion and excision as a means of DNA repair.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] UDG is made of a four-stranded parallel β-sheet surrounded by eight α-helices.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Glycosidic bond cleavage follows a “pinch-push-pull” mechanism using the five conserved motifs.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] The position of the residues that activate the water nucleophile and protonate the uracil leaving group are widely debated, though the most commonly followed mechanism employs the water activating loop detailed in the enzyme structure.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Regardless of position, the identities of the aspartic acid and histidine residues are consistent across catalytic studies.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Uracil *N*-glycosylase (UNG) is utilized to eliminate carryover polymerase chain reaction (PCR) products in PCR.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] This method modifies PCR products such that in a new reaction, any residual products from previous PCR amplifications will be digested and prevented from amplifying, but the true DNA templates will be unaffected.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] PCR synthesizes abundant amplification products each round, but contamination of further rounds of PCR with trace amounts of these products, called carry-over contamination, yields false positive results.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Carry-over contamination from some previous PCR can be a significant problem, due both to the abundance of PCR products, and to the ideal structure of the contaminant material for re-amplification.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] UDG cleaves the uracil base from the phosphodiester backbone of uracil-containing DNA, but has no effect on natural (i.e., thymine-containing) DNA.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] The resulting apyrimidinic sites block replication by DNA polymerases, and are very labile to acid/base hydrolysis.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Because UDG does not react with dTTP, and is also inactivated by heat denaturation prior to the actual PCR, carry-over contamination of PCRs can be controlled effectively if the contaminants contain uracils in place of thymines.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Subsequent studies have reported that residual uracil-DNA glycosylase activity may persist after thermal cycling, potentially affecting downstream applications involving uracil-containing PCR products.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] To address this limitation, thermolabile uracil-DNA glycosylases from cold-adapted organisms such as Atlantic cod (*Gadus morhua*) have been characterized and shown to undergo rapid thermal inactivation while maintaining activity at lower temperatures.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Uracil *N*-glycosylase was also used in a study to detect evidence of ongoing low-level metabolic activity and DNA repair in ancient bacteria.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] DNA sequences from bacteria in permafrost were amplified using PCR.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] One series of runs amplified the DNA sequences as-is (to detect all live bacterial DNA in the samples), while the other series looked specifically for DNA that had been undergoing ongoing repair; to do this, the DNA was treated with UNG to remove uracils.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] In this way, the researchers were able to show evidence of ongoing DNA repair in high-GC Gram-positive bacteria up to 600,000 years old.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Uracil N glycosylase has also been used in a method for cloning of PCR amplified DNA fragments.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] In this method the primers used in PCR are synthesized with uracil residues instead of thymine.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] When these primers are incorporated into PCR amplified fragments the primer sequence becomes susceptible to digestion with Uracil N Glycosylase and produce 3' protruding ends that can be annealed to an appropriately prepared vector DNA.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] The resulting chimeric molecules can be transformed into competent cells with high efficiency, without the need for in vitro ligation.
[src:base-editing/uracil-dna-glycosylase] Uracil-DNA glycosylase has been shown to interact with RPA2.
